MiniScript uses `//` for comments. Everything from `//` to the end of the line is ignored by the compiler. There is no block comment syntax (like `/* */` in some other languages), so each comment line needs its own `//`.

Here are some examples:

```
// This is a full-line comment

x = 42  // This is an inline comment after a statement

// You can use comments to explain logic:
// Calculate the area of a circle
radius = 5
area = pi * radius ^ 2
print "Area: " + area

// Comments are handy for temporarily disabling code:
// print "This line won't run"
```

Since there are no multi-line block comments, if you need to comment out a larger section, just put `//` at the start of each line:

```
// This function is not ready yet:
// myFunc = function(x)
//     return x * 2
// end function
```
